Red Wine Exploration by Julie Tang

========================================================

This report explores a dataset containing the quality and attributes of 1599 red wine samples.

Quality is a discrete quantitative variable. The range of quality variable is from 3(lowest) to 8(highest). And the most common level of qualities are 5 and 6. 681 samples’ quality rate is 5 and 638 samples’ quality rate is 6.

The pH is normal distributed. The mean is 3.311 and the median is 3.310, which are very close. According to some experts’ opinion, pH is one of the most important attributes on the wine’s quality. It affects almost every aspect of the wine, including the quality. I wondered what’s its correlation with quality in our dataset.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1599 samples in the dataset with 13 variables. 11 are attributes that might impact the quality (fixed.acidity, volatile.acidity,, citric.acid, residual.sugar, chlorides, free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide, density, pH, sulphates and alcohol). All these attributes are quantitative variables. Variable quality is the output variable, which is also the one we are intersted in. Quality is also quantified.

Other observations:
1. Most of samples’ quality rate is 5 or 6.
2. The density of all samples are very close. It has a very narrow range(from 0.9901 to 1.0037). It seems it doesn’t impact the quality much.
3. The median percent alcohol content is 10.2. But there are a few outlier with value higher than 14.
4. The median pH value is 3.31 and it’s normal distributed.
5. There are some outliers with very high free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide. Since high sulphates is not good for health and according to experts’ opinion, it impact the taste of the wine too. Does higher wine quality generally have lower sulphate/Sulfur dioxide content?

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of interest in the dataset is quality. I want to check which attributes have most important impact on the wine’s quality.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Acidity, residual sugar, chlorides, sulfur dioxide, density, pH, sulphates and alcohol likely all contribute to the quality of red wine. I think pH and sulphates might contribute most to the quality according to some experts’ opinion on the wine quality.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

Yes. I created a new variables named “all.sulphates”. Since sulfur dioxide is just another type of sulphates, I think it makes sense to add them up together to see what impact they have on the quality.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

I log-transformed the right skewed free.sulfur.dioxide, total.sulfur.dioxide, sulphates and all.surphates distribution. The transformed distribution for these variables appeal close to normal. The median of all.surphates is 38.56. I also noticed there are some outliers with super high surphate content.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

To be honest, I don’t see any attribute has strong correlation with quality. It’s hard to say which attribute is most critical to predict the wine’s quality. Though from correlation coefficient’s perspective, the alcohol is most correlated with quality, the corrlation is still not strong.

But when putting alcohol, sulphates and quality in the same plot, we can see generally the samples with higher alcohol and higher sulphates(but lower than 1) has the trend to be higher quality. This is reasonable because both alcohol and sulphate (under 1) have positive correlation with quality.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

pH seems can’t predict the quality at all. While doing the research to understand what might contribute to wine’s quality, pH seems always be the top one. I suppose the plot should show some correlation between pH and quality. But no matter where I add pH it spreads everywhere.

OPTIONAL: Did you create any models with your dataset? Discuss the
strengths and limitations of your model.

Yes, I created a linear model that included alcohol, sulphates, pH and volatile acidity variables and wine quality as the output variable. The limitation of this linear model is that variables in this linear model can only account for 34.9% of the variance in the quality of red wine. The strengths is that we can still tell some correlations between the predictors and output variable and by adding additonal variable we got higher r-squared value.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This Plot shows the relationship between pH and quality. I excluded the samples with bottom 1% and top 1% of pH to explain the majority of samples to avoid the interrupt of extreme cases. Though there is no direct correlation between pH and quality, we can see pH is mostly between 3.1 and 3.5 for the samples with high quality(7 or 8). Since the majority samples’ pH is between 3.0 and 3.7, the range is narrow. Maybe that can also explain why we don’t see much correlation between pH and quality. When pH is above 3.6, we can see there are few samples with high quality. If the pH’s range is bigger, maybe we can see its impact on the quality.

Plot Two

Description Two

The plot above shows the correlation between pH and fixed acidity. The correlation between these two attributes are the strongest among all the attributes. I split the quality level into 3 buckets:(2,4],(4, 6], (6, 8]. It’s interesting to see that if we use lm smoothing method, the slope of higher quality is steeper than the lower quality.

Plot Three

Description Three

Both alcohol and sulphates have positive correlation with quality. When putting these three variables together, we can see there is a mild trend: higher alcohol, higer sulphates(under 1) have higher quality. But the correlation is not strong. Also, there are few samples have sulphates higher than 1.0.

Reflection

When I started to explore the red wine dataset, I was very confused on what each variable means since I’m not familiar with wine at all. I did some research on google and read some articles to get better understanding. According to some articles, I believe pH and Sulphates are the most important attributes that impact the quality. So I decided to focus on the relationship between these two attributes and quality.

However, I was surprised I didn’t see strong correlations between them and quality at all, especially pH. In the plots sulphates shows mild positive correlation with quality(corr is 0.251). I had been thinking why this happened during the whole exploration. Surprisingly, Alcohol shows the strong correlation with quality among all the attributes(corr is 0.476).

After I explore more and more, I think the reason this happened is because that there is some limitation on the dataset. There are 1599 samples in total. And 1,319 out of 1,599 received a score of 5 or 6. No sample received scores of 0, 1, 9, or 10. Since the wine quality variable had such limited variability, it was difficult to assess the relationship between quality and the chemical attribute variables. If we have a greater variety of quality ratings we might get a better insight on how these attributes are related with quality. Also, quality rating is based on sensory data (median of at least 3 evaluations made by wine experts). It’s difficult to accurately describe and quantify.

Besides the attributes in the dataset, there are some other aspects that impact the quality, like the type of grape, the place and climate where the grape grow etc. There is another dataset of white wine, which I would like to do another exploration to compare with the data of red wine to see if there is any different pattern.
